div.div: How Execution price is calculated in Uniswap?

In automated market makers, such as Uniswap, the amount of tokens that you will receive depends on the amount of tokens that you will sent in a non-linear fashion: the more liquidity you remove from the pool, the less tokens you will receive in the final. If you do not take fees into account, the reserve of pairs X and Y must satisfy the following invariant on each swap: Xold Yold = Xnew Ynew Thus, by sending X to the pool, you will receive Y according to the formula: Y = (Y X)/(X + X) The execution price is defined as Y/X, that is, Execution price = Y/(X+X) Note that the mid-price (defined as Y/X) approximates the execution price as X approximates 0. That is why Uniswap states that the mid-price "represents the price at which you could theoretically trade an infinitesimal amount () of one token for the other". However, in practice, you will pay the execution price since you also pay for removing liquidity from the pool.
